To create buttons that flee from the mouse cursor, you can use a combination of JavaScript to track mouse position and CSS for styling and animation. Here's a basic example:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Fleeing Button</title>
  <style>
    #fleeButton {
      position: absolute;
      padding: 10px 20px;
      background: #ff6b6b;
      color: white;
      border: none;
      border-radius: 5px;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: all 0.3s ease;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <button id="fleeButton">Click Me!</button>

  <script>
    const button = document.getElementById('fleeButton');
    const body = document.body;

    body.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
      const x = e.clientX;
      const y = e.clientY;

      // Calculate new position to move away from cursor
      const newX = x < window.innerWidth / 2 ? x + 100 : x - 100;
      const newY = y < window.innerHeight / 2 ? y + 50 : y - 50;

      // Apply new position
      button.style.left = `${newX}px`;
      button.style.top = `${newY}px`;
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>

In this example, the button moves away from the mouse cursor whenever it moves. Adjust the offset values (100px horizontally, 50px vertically) to change the fleeing behavior.
